servings: 2
author: Mimi Morley
course: main course
time required: 30 minutes
---

Zest and juice the @lime{1}. Put the juice in a #mixing bowl{} and set the zest aside for later. Cut each @whiting fillet{4} into four pieces and add to the bowl with the juice. Season with a pinch of @salt{} and a good grind of @ground black pepper{}. Set aside to marinate.

Pour the @water for the rice{300%ml} into a large #saucepan{} with half the @vegetable stock powder{1%pot} and the @cardamom pod{1}. Bring to the boil, stir to dissolve the stock pot and add the @basmati rice{150%g}. Bring back to the boil, cover with a #lid{} and cook on medium-low heat for ~{10%minutes}. Then remove from the heat and set aside for another ~{10%minutes}.

> The rice will finish cooking in its own steam.

Meanwhile, halve, peel and chop the @onion{1} into roughly 1cm pieces. Peel and grate the @garlic clove{1} (or use a #garlic press{}). Trim the tops from the @green beans{150%g} and chop them into thirds.

Heat a drizzle of @oil{} in a #frying pan{} on medium heat and add the @mustard seeds{1}. Once they begin to pop, add the onion and lime zest. Cook on low heat until the onion is soft, ~{5%minutes}, then add the @Sri Lankan curry powder{2%tbsp} and garlic. Cook for ~{1%minute} more.

> If you leave the mustard seeds for too long on their own they'll start jumping out of the pan, so make sure you keep an eye on them!

Pour the @coconut milk{200%ml} and the @water for the curry{50%ml} into your pan. Add the remaining vegetable stock pot and the green beans. Stir everything together. Simmer gently for ~{2-3%minutes}.

Carefully add the fish along with any lime juice left in the bowl. Gently submerge it in the sauce but be careful not to break the pieces up. Cover with a lid (or some foil) and poach the fish on low heat, ~{4-5%minutes}. Remove the cardamom pods from the rice and fluff it up with a #fork{}. Serve your delicious fish curry atop a generous heap of rice. Enjoy!